Title: Diagnosis of test `testGenerateURLFragment`
Details: The test `testGenerateURLFragment` checks whether HTML entities such as `"` are correctly escaped to their corresponding character by the `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` method. Consequently, un-escaped strings are being returned, which leads to the error demonstrated by the test.

The `testNumericKeys` method in the `CodePrinterTest` class has the following code snippet:

```java
public void testNumericKeys() {
    assertPrint("var x = {'010': 1};", "var x={\"010\":1}"); // error occurred here
}
```

The error occurred at the assertion where the expected output was `"var x={["010"]:1}"` but the actual output was `"var x={[10]:1}"`. This indicates a discrepancy in the handling of numeric keys in an object literal. The expected output seems to have an issue with the syntax of the numeric key.

Given the methods we have explored so far, the issue with handling numeric keys in object literals in the `CodePrinter` class could potentially be in a method that formats the code. To resolve the discrepancy in the numeric key representation, the following method could be a good candidate for inspection and potential fixes:

```
CodePrinter.toSource(com.google.javascript.rhino.Node, com.google.javascript.jscomp.CodePrinter.Format, boolean, int, com.google.javascript.jscomp.SourceMap, com.google.javascript.jscomp.SourceMap.DetailLevel, java.nio.charset.Charset, boolean)
```

This method seems to be responsible for converting a JavaScript node to source code. Investigating this method may help in identifying and fixing the issue with how numeric keys are handled in object literals.
